# How I Measure Engineering Health

Velocity is not health. Shipping fast while burning people out and accumulating debt is not success — it's a loan you'll pay back with interest.

## What I actually watch

**Deployment frequency and lead time.** How often are we shipping? How long does it take from code complete to production? These tell me about our process health, not just our output.

**Incident rate and recovery time.** How often do things break? When they do, how fast do we recover? A team with great recovery culture is more resilient than a team that never has incidents but falls apart when they do.

**Technical debt load.** Is the team spending more time fighting the codebase than building on top of it? I track this qualitatively through team conversation and quantitatively through the ratio of maintenance to new work.

**Team retention and engagement.** If my best people are leaving or quietly disengaging, something is wrong — with the work, the culture, the direction, or me. I pay attention to this before it becomes a trend.

**Psychological safety signals.** Are people raising problems early? Are retrospectives honest? Is anyone consistently quiet who shouldn't be? These are health indicators I take as seriously as any technical metric.

## What I don't overindex on

Story points. Lines of code. Individual productivity metrics. These measure activity, not outcomes. I care about what we shipped, what it did, and how the team is doing — not how many tickets got closed.

## How I use this

I share health signals with my team. Not to create anxiety — to create shared ownership. A team that understands its own health can improve it. A team that only hears about problems from leadership can't.
